Max Cleland was a Vietnam War veteran who lost both of his legs and his right arm in a grenade explosion. Despite his injuries, Cleland continued to serve the public and became a champion for working people and wounded veterans. He played a key role in the creation of the modern VA health system. Cleland was known for his patriotism, courage, and character. The author, who worked with Cleland in the United States Senate, describes him as a great leader. Cleland passed away, and the author expresses sadness and offers prayers for those who loved him.